#. type: Title =====
#: source/securing_apps/topics/saml/mod-auth-mellon.adoc:58
#, no-wrap
msgid "Configuring the Mellon Service Provider"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/securing_apps/topics/saml/mod-auth-mellon.adoc:61
#, no-wrap
msgid "Configuration files for Apache add-on modules are located in the /etc/httpd/conf.d directory and have a file name extension of .conf. You need to create the /etc/httpd/conf.d/mellon.conf file and place Mellon's configuration directives in it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/securing_apps/topics/saml/mod-auth-mellon.adoc:63
#, no-wrap
msgid "Mellon's configuration directives can roughly be broken down into two classes of information:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/securing_apps/topics/saml/mod-auth-mellon.adoc:65
#, no-wrap
msgid "Which URLs to protect with SAML authentication\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/securing_apps/topics/saml/mod-auth-mellon.adoc:66
#, no-wrap
msgid "What SAML parameters will be used when a protected URL is referenced.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/securing_apps/topics/saml/mod-auth-mellon.adoc:68
#, no-wrap
msgid "Apache configuration directives typically follow a hierarchical tree structure in the URL space, which are known as locations. You need to specify one or more URL locations for Mellon to protect. You have flexibility in how you add the configuration parameters that apply to each location. You can either add all the necessary parameters to the location block or you can add Mellon parameters to a common location high up in the URL location hierarchy that specific protected locations inherit (or some combination of the two). Since it is common for an SP to operate in the same way no matter which location triggers SAML actions, the example configuration used here places common Mellon configuration directives in the root of the hierarchy and then specific locations to be protected by Mellon can be defined with minimal directives. This strategy avoids duplicating the same parameters for each protected location.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/securing_apps/topics/saml/mod-auth-mellon.adoc:70
#, no-wrap
msgid "This example has just one protected location: \\https://$sp_host/protected.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/securing_apps/topics/saml/mod-auth-mellon.adoc:72
#, no-wrap
msgid "To configure the Mellon service provider, complete the following steps:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/securing_apps/topics/saml/mod-auth-mellon.adoc:74
#, no-wrap
msgid "Create the file /etc/httpd/conf.d/mellon.conf with this content:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block -
#: source/securing_apps/topics/saml/mod-auth-mellon.adoc:90
#, no-wrap
msgid " <Location / >\n"
"    MellonEnable info\n"
"    MellonEndpointPath /mellon/\n"
"    MellonSPMetadataFile /etc/httpd/saml2/mellon_metadata.xml\n"
"    MellonSPPrivateKeyFile /etc/httpd/saml2/mellon.key\n"
"    MellonSPCertFile /etc/httpd/saml2/mellon.crt\n"
"    MellonIdPMetadataFile /etc/httpd/saml2/idp_metadata.xml\n"
" </Location>\n"
" <Location /private >\n"
"    AuthType Mellon\n"
"    MellonEnable auth\n"
"    Require valid-user\n"
" </Location>\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/securing_apps/topics/saml/mod-auth-mellon.adoc:93
#, no-wrap
msgid "Some of the files referenced in the code above are created in later steps.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title =====
#: source/securing_apps/topics/saml/mod-auth-mellon.adoc:94
#, no-wrap
msgid "Creating the Service Provider Metadata"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/securing_apps/topics/saml/mod-auth-mellon.adoc:97
#, no-wrap
msgid "In SAML IdPs and SPs exchange SAML metadata, which is in XML format. The schema for the metadata is a standard, thus assuring participating SAML entities can consume each other's metadata. You need:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/securing_apps/topics/saml/mod-auth-mellon.adoc:99
#, no-wrap
msgid "Metadata for the IdP that the SP utilizes\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/securing_apps/topics/saml/mod-auth-mellon.adoc:100
#, no-wrap
msgid "Metadata describing the SP provided to the IdP\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/securing_apps/topics/saml/mod-auth-mellon.adoc:102
#, no-wrap
msgid "One of the components of SAML metadata is X509 certificates. These certificates are used for two purposes:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/securing_apps/topics/saml/mod-auth-mellon.adoc:104
#, no-wrap
msgid "Sign SAML messages so the receiving end can prove the message originated from the expected party.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/securing_apps/topics/saml/mod-auth-mellon.adoc:105
#, no-wrap
msgid "Encrypt the message during transport (seldom used because SAML messages typically occur on TLS-protected transports)\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/securing_apps/topics/saml/mod-auth-mellon.adoc:107
#, no-wrap
msgid "You can use your own certificates if you already have a Certificate Authority (CA) or you can generate a self-signed certificate. For simplicity in this example a self-signed certificate is used.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/securing_apps/topics/saml/mod-auth-mellon.adoc:109
#, no-wrap
msgid "Because Mellon's SP metadata must reflect the capabilities of the installed version of mod_auth_mellon, must be valid SP metadata XML, and must contain an X509 certificate (whose creation can be obtuse unless you are familiar with X509 certificate generation) the most expedient way to produce the SP metadata is to use a tool included in the mod_auth_mellon package (mellon_create_metadata.sh). The generated metadata can always be edited later because it is a text file. The tool also creates your X509 key and certificate.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/securing_apps/topics/saml/mod-auth-mellon.adoc:111
#, no-wrap
msgid "SAML IdPs and SPs identify themselves using a unique name known as an EntityID. To use the Mellon metadata creation tool you need:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/securing_apps/topics/saml/mod-auth-mellon.adoc:113
#, no-wrap
msgid "The EntityID, which is typically the URL of the SP, and often the URL of the SP where the SP metadata can be retrieved\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/securing_apps/topics/saml/mod-auth-mellon.adoc:114
#, no-wrap
msgid "The URL where SAML messages for the SP will be consumed, which Mellon calls the MellonEndPointPath.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/securing_apps/topics/saml/mod-auth-mellon.adoc:116
#, no-wrap
msgid "To create the SP metadata, complete the following steps:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/securing_apps/topics/saml/mod-auth-mellon.adoc:118
#, no-wrap
msgid "Create a few helper shell variables: \n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block -
#: source/securing_apps/topics/saml/mod-auth-mellon.adoc:125
#, no-wrap
msgid "fqdn=`hostname`\n"
"mellon_endpoint_url=\"https://${fqdn}/mellon\"\n"
"mellon_entity_id=\"${mellon_endpoint_url}/metadata\"\n"
"file_prefix=\"$(echo \"$mellon_entity_id\" | sed 's/[^A-Za-z.]/_/g' | sed 's/__*/_/g')\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/securing_apps/topics/saml/mod-auth-mellon.adoc:128
#, no-wrap
msgid "Invoke the Mellon metadata creation tool by running this command:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block -
#: source/securing_apps/topics/saml/mod-auth-mellon.adoc:132
#, no-wrap
msgid "/usr/libexec/mod_auth_mellon/mellon_create_metadata.sh $mellon_entity_id $mellon_endpoint_url\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: source/securing_apps/topics/saml/mod-auth-mellon.adoc:135
#, no-wrap
msgid "Move the generated files to their destination (referenced in the /etc/httpd/conf.d/mellon.conf file created above):\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: delimited block -
#: source/securing_apps/topics/saml/mod-auth-mellon.adoc:141
#, no-wrap
msgid "mv ${file_prefix}.cert /etc/httpd/saml2/mellon.crt\n"
"mv ${file_prefix}.key /etc/httpd/saml2/mellon.key\n"
"mv ${file_prefix}.xml /etc/httpd/saml2/mellon_metadata.xml\n"
msgstr ""

